{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471903"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:52:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:52:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"879"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/879"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.12,0.7,0.04,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"879"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53301"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/879"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"879"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38745"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"565"},{"type":"tags","id":"857"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"},{"type":"tags","id":"9689"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1939"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8422"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8464"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14980"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15591"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53301"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-day-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a 24-hour history of vomiting green material and poor feeding. He has not yet passed meconium. He has no significant medical history and was born at term via normal vaginal delivery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 130/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 50/min, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. His abdomen is generally distended. An ultrasound scan shows malposition of the superior mesenteric arteries.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the definitive treatment for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gastrografin enema","Nasogastric tube insertion and intravenous antibiotics","Ladd procedure","Rectal biopsy","Pyloromyotomy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis neonate has presented with signs and symptoms suggestive of midgut volvulus, confirmed by the malposition of the superior mesenteric vessels (whirlpool sign) on ultrasound. Midgut volvulus typically presents with acute upper bowel obstruction and bilious vomiting. It is caused by a torsion of the midgut around the superior mesenteric vessels, resulting from abnormal rotation of the midgut during development, leading to a narrow base of the midgut mesentery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in management is prompt surgical intervention with a \u003Cstrong\u003ELadd procedure\u003C/strong\u003E. This is crucial as delayed intervention significantly increases the risk of bowel ischaemia and necrosis. The Ladd procedure involves detorsion of the twisted midgut and division of any abnormal intraperitoneal bands. When performed early, it can restore bowel perfusion and ensure viability. An appendectomy is often performed during the procedure due to the potential abnormal position of the appendix post-correction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENasogastric tube insertion and intravenous antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E may be part of the supportive care adjacent to surgery but cannot be considered definitive management for this surgical emergency. These measures alone would not address the underlying volvulus and risk of bowel ischaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastrografin enema\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used as a definitive treatment for uncomplicated meconium ileus, a condition where abnormally viscid meconium causes intraluminal neonatal intestinal obstruction. While water-soluble contrast studies can be useful in diagnosing midgut volvulus, they are not appropriate for management in this emergency situation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERectal biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard for diagnosing Hirschsprung\u0027s disease, another important differential for neonatal bowel obstruction. However, it is not indicated in the management of midgut volvulus, which is the likely diagnosis in this case based on the clinical presentation and ultrasound findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyloromyotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the surgical treatment for congenital pyloric stenosis. However, pyloric stenosis typically presents with non-bilious vomiting and usually evolves over the first 3-6 weeks of life, making it an unlikely diagnosis in this four-day-old neonate with bilious vomiting.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ladd procedure is the definitive management for midgut volvulus occurring in neonates.","Bilious vomiting in a neonate is a surgical emergency until proven otherwise.","Malposition of superior mesenteric vessels on ultrasound (whirlpool sign) is diagnostic of midgut volvulus."],"references":["Gaillard F.\u00a0Midgut volvulus. In: Radiopaedia.org [online]. 2021. Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/midgut-volvulus","Clinical Practice Guidelines: Abdominal Pain - Acute. In: Royal Children\u0027s Hospital [online]. 2019. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guidelineindex/AbdominalPain-Acute/.","Clinical Practice Guidelines: Intussusception. In: Royal Children\u0027s Hospital [online]. 2019. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guidelineindex/IntussusceptionGuideline/","Saberi RA, Gilna GP, Slavin BV, Cioci AC, Urrechaga EM, Parreco JP, et al. Outcomes for Ladd\u0027s procedure: Does approach matter? Journal of Pediatric Surgery. 2022;57(1):141-6. Available at: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0022346821006278"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38745"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"879"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38745"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-18T12:12:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-18T12:13:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"879"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53301"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tag